## What's covered

**Email** — string-type guard, RFC 5321 length cap (254), full RFC parsing + unicode/IDN→punycode normalization via `email-validator` (with regex fallback), control/zero-width/bidi stripping, disposable-domain blocking, and a **canonical form** (lowercase + gmail dot/`+tag` folding) stored in a separate `UNIQUE` column so `a.b+x@gmail.com` and `ab@gmail.com` can't both register.

**Username** — type guard, 3–30 length, strict charset regex (must start/end alphanumeric), no repeated separators, reserved-word denylist, **homoglyph folding** (Cyrillic/Greek/leet → Latin) re-checked against reserved words, offensive-fragment check, and **mixed-script rejection** (classic spoofing vector).

**Password** — **max-length cap (128) checked before hashing** to prevent argon2 hashing-DoS, min 12, upper/lower/digit/symbol composition, common-password denylist, breach-check hook (HIBP k-anonymity, documented), no-whitespace/no-control, **no-similarity to username/email**, repeated-char and sequential-run rejection. Hashed with **argon2id** (`argon2-cffi`), never reversible/SHA/MD5.

**Security** — **parameterized queries** throughout (no concatenation); **rate limiting** (per-IP sliding window); **account-enumeration prevention** (identical neutral `201` whether the account is new or duplicate, plus a **timing equalizer** dummy-verify + `hmac.compare_digest` on the duplicate path); duplicate/concurrent signups resolved **atomically by DB `UNIQUE` constraints**, not a check-then-insert race; `extra="forbid"` rejects unexpected fields; proper status codes (`400`/`422`/`429`/`201`/`500`).

**Edge cases** — NFC normalization, whitespace collapse, control/format-char stripping, optional `display_name` defaulting to username, and a **collect-all-errors** response shape (`errors: [{field, message}, ...]`).

## Two deliberate non-fakes worth calling out
- **XSS**: `display_name` is stored raw (control chars stripped) — XSS is correctly prevented at *output* time via context-aware encoding in the view layer. Escaping on input corrupts data and causes double-encoding.
- **CSRF**: not applicable to a token-based JSON API with no ambient cookie auth. The code comments document exactly what to add (`SameSite=strict` + synchronizer/double-submit token) *if* cookie sessions are introduced. Other transport concerns (HTTPS/HSTS, CSP, body-size limits) belong at the nginx/ASGI layer and are noted rather than mocked.

